The four vessels of the Baden-Wuerttemberg class ordered by the Navy in 2007 serve to replace the obsolete frigates of the Bremen class.
As far as we know, they have a powerful cannon, a range of air-rescue and anti-ship missiles and a form of stealth technology, such as reduced radar, infrared and acoustic features.
Other important features are longer maintenance cycles, it should be possible to put the latest frigates together for up to two years, far from home ports.
The constant delays, however, mean that the advanced warships, which are intended to allow Germany to project its power overseas, are already outdated by the time they are put into service, notes Die Zeit.
The fatal frigate F125 had already taken the newspaper heads last year, when the German Navy officially refused to put the vessel into service and sent it back to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
This was the first time the Navy sent a ship back to a shipbuilder after delivery.
There is little known of the reasons behind this return, but German media cited a number of crucial 'software and hardware defects' that would make the warship useless if it were deployed in a combat mission.
Software defects were particularly important because the vessels of the Baden-Wuerttemberg class are operated by a crew of about 120 sailors, half the manpower on the frigates of the older Bremen class.
It also became clear that the ship is suffering from severe overweight, which will reduce its performance and limit its capabilities to further upgrades.
The 'Rheinland-Pfalz' weighs 7,000 tons, twice as much as ships of a similar class used by the Germans in the Second World War.
In addition to the defective hardware, the price tag for the full project, including the training of the crew, will also become a problem.
It is said that this has reached a staggering €3.1 billion compared to the original €2.2 billion.
The problems that the newest frigates have in their grip are becoming particularly important because of recent warnings that the power of the German Navy is diminishing.
Earlier this year, Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the German parliamentary defence committee, acknowledged that the marine actually has "a shortage of deployable ships".
The official said that the problem over time has grown as a snowball, because old ships were taken out of operation but no replacement vessels were delivered.
