National Trust listens to the secret life of bats
New research carried out on a farm in the Scottish highlands is trying to reveal how bats use the landscape in their search for food.
The hope is that the findings will give new light to the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and will contribute to future conservation activities.
The study conducted by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland follows the common and small dwarf bat, the brown large ear bat and the water bat at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recording equipment is placed at key locations around the estate to track the activities of bats throughout the season.
Employees of the NTS and volunteers will also carry out mobile research using hand detectors.
Expert sound analysis of all recordings will determine the frequency of the screams of the bat and what kind does.
Next, a map of the habitat and a report is produced to provide a detailed picture of their behaviour on a landscape scale.
Rob Dewar, NTS Nature Conservation Advisor, hopes that the results show which areas of the habitat are the most important for bats and how they are used by the species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management, such as the creation of pastures and how we can best maintain forests for bats and similar species.
Bat populations in Scotland and the rest of the UK have decreased significantly in the last century.
They are threatened by construction and development activities that affect sleeping places and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lightning may also pose a risk, as may fly trappers and certain chemical treatments of building materials and house cat attacks.
Bats are not really blind.
Their nightly hunting habits, however, make their ears more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching a prey.
They use an advanced echo location technique to determine the position of insects and obstacles in their flight path.
At the NTS, which is responsible for caring for more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares ashore in the country, bats are taken very seriously.
The NTS has ten trained experts who carry out regular examinations, inspection of sleeping places and sometimes rescue operations.
The organization has even set up the first and only reservation for bats in Scotland at the Threeave estate in Dumfries and Galloway, where eight of the ten species of bats in Scotland live.
Landscape manager David Thompson says that the estate is the ideal territory for bats.
"Here in Threeave we have a great environment for bats," he said.
"We have the old buildings, many very old trees and the right habitat.
But there is so much about bats not yet known and therefore the work we do here and at other locations will help us better understand what they need to thrive."
He stressed the importance of controlling bats before maintenance operations are carried out, since the possible unconscious destruction of a sleeping place could lead to the death of 400 female bats and their boy, possibly eliminating a complete local population.
Bats are a protected animal species and it is illegal to kill them, to fall or to disturb them or to destroy their sleeping places.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish officer for the Bat Conservation Trust, has asked the public to make a contribution to help.
She said, "We still have to learn a lot about our bats and many of our species we just don't know how to deal with their populations."
